data.content:
Yes! MSTest 3.3+ supports **tuple-based `DynamicData`**, eliminating the `object[]` boxing and giving you compile-time type safety:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**Key changes:**
- `IEnumerable<object[]>` → `IEnumerable<(string, bool)>` (ValueTuple)
- Array literals `["x", true]` → tuple literals `("x", true)`

This gives you compile-time errors if you mix up types in your test data, and better IDE support. The framework automatically decomposes the tuple into the method parameters by position.

For simple constant data, `[DataRow]` is even simpler:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

Use `DynamicData` with tuples when your data is computed or too complex for `[DataRow]` (which only accepts compile-time constants).
